Image pull secrets.

If your pod runs an image from a private registry, the kube-let on the node needs credentials to pull it. That is exactly what image pull secrets are for. There are two steps.

Step one, create the credential as a secret. You use kubectl create secret docker registry, passing the registry server, a username, and a password. That builds a secret of the docker config json type, whose data is an encoded docker configuration blob.

Step two, reference it from the pod spec. You add an image pull secrets list naming that secret, alongside the container that uses the private image. That is it. The kube-let uses the credential to authenticate when pulling the image. Importantly, the secret is used only for the image pull. The running container never sees it as an environment variable or a file.

There is also a cluster wide alternative. If every pod in a namespace needs the same registry credential, you can set it once on the namespace's default service account, and skip the per pod image pull secrets entirely. You patch the default service account to include the credential, and from then on every pod created in that namespace that does not override the service account picks it up automatically.

That is the more scalable pattern in a real cluster. Attach the credential to the service account once, rather than repeating it in every pod template. Service accounts get full treatment later, alongside are-back.
